</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Loriol" baseAuthorityYear="1876" box="[989,1137,1986,2011]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="robillardi">
<emphasis box="[989,1137,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">M. robillardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The lack of coalescence between the aboralmost regions of the posterior paired petals is very different from the situation seen in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="sternalis">M. sternalis</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[261,412,188,213]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="townsendi">M. townsendi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs in having a subcentral position of the apical system, and much lower anterior end of the test.
</paragraph>
