<paragraph blockId="81.[151,1436,1944,2005]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Forms that lack the anterior notch, lack the coalescence, and have the apical system at least somewhat anterior, as in the new species, include 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1917" box="[489,613,1980,2005]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="dicrana">
<emphasis box="[489,613,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">M. dicrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[628,741,1980,2005]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[628,741,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">M. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[802,940,1981,2004]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="spatagus">
<emphasis box="[802,940,1981,2004]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">M. spatagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="82.[151,1436,151,645]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[199,313,151,176]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[199,313,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">M. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1855" box="[428,515,151,176]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[428,515,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Metalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known from the Americas, has small petals relative to its congeners. In addition, the periproct in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1855" box="[331,418,188,213]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[331,418,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Metalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
n. sp. is directed downwards and is not fully visible from the aboral side. This is not only unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[229,344,223,248]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[229,344,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">M. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is not like 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[503,642,225,248]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="spatagus">
<emphasis box="[503,642,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">M. spatagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
either, which has a more vertical posterior region with at least part of the periproct visible in aboral view. This is also true for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1917" box="[786,911,260,285]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="dicrana">
<emphasis box="[786,911,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">M. dicrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1855" box="[1349,1436,260,285]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1349,1436,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Metalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its peculiar double point along the sternum just adoral to the subanal fasciole (Mooi, unpubl. data). Therefore, the specimens are very unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1917" box="[491,615,332,357]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="dicrana">
<emphasis box="[491,615,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">M. dicrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="82.[151,1436,151,645]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
The Sri Lankan specimens of this new form have a very distinctive, concave region below the periproct which has not been noted in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1855" box="[461,548,404,429]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Metalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[461,548,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Metalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<figureCitation box="[652,735,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 70" captionStartId="80.[151,250,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1798]" captionTargetId="figure@80.[151,1436,193,1798]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURE 70. Metalia sp. (WUSL/EI/85): A, sternal view; B, subanal fasciole view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617595/files/figure.png" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
), although it does occur to some degree in some of the species (Mooi, unpubl. data). As discovered by 
<bibRefCitation author="Askin, R. &amp; Mooi, R." box="[596,841,439,464]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" pagination="7" refId="ref33641" refString="Askin, R. &amp; Mooi, R. (2017) The heart of the problem: Phylogenetic systematics of burrowing sea urchins in the genus Metalia (Echinoidea: Spatangoida). Integrative and Comparative Biology, 57 (Supplement 1), e 7." type="journal article" year="2017">Askin &amp; Mooi (2017)</bibRefCitation>
using molecular techniques, it would appear that this is a new species. It was depicted by van 
<bibRefCitation author="van Noordenburg, H." box="[617,851,476,501]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" refId="ref36274" refString="van Noordenburg, H. (2008) Sea Urchins of the Philippines. Part I. The Irregulars. Artificial Harmonics, Utrecht, 153 pp." type="book" year="2008">Noordenburg (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, but remains unnamed pending further work on the abundant material at the 
<collectingRegion box="[428,542,511,536]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">California</collectingRegion>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2147524161" box="[548,1263,511,536]" location="Academy of Sciences" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Wien">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:038087B4FFE78927FF02FDD872369BE8:8EF66079FFF88927FDB1FE4B70039B74" box="[548,791,511,536]" name="Academy of Sciences" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" stateProvince="Wien">Academy of Sciences</location>
and the Natural History Museum, 
<collectingRegion box="[1180,1263,511,536]" country="Austria" name="Wien" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Vienna</collectingRegion>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="82.[151,1436,151,645]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
Variation in the path of the peripetalous fasciole was noted in collected specimens. WUSL/IE/E85 shows shallow aborally-curved segments in interambulacrum 4, and one sharply defined indentation in interambulacrum 1 (
<figureCitation box="[159,242,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 68" captionStartId="78.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,301,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@78.[151,1436,301,1906]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURE 68. Metalia sp. (WUSL/EI/85): A, aboral view; B, oral view; C, lateral view; D, anterior view; E, posterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617591/files/figure.png" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
, A).
</paragraph>
